{
  "doc_id": "9408",
  "text": "Malignant glioma is one of the most aggressive tumors with a poor prognosis despite the available treatments [CITATION_1] . Standard treatment procedures, consisting of surgery and radiation therapy (followed by adjuvant chemotherapy), very often fail due to the inability to accurately delineate tumor margins [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , and the median survival time for patients with recurrent glioblastoma multiforme (GBM) is less than 1 year [CITATION_5] . The infiltrative nature of GBM is considered to be one of the main factors impeding the complete removal of tumor mass by surgical procedure [CITATION_6] . Following radiation therapy or surgery, recurrence is common and almost invariably occurs within ,2 cm of the prior resection line. Detection of recurring tumor at an early stage using current in vivo imaging techniques is difficult, mainly due to normal tissue damage that occurs following radiation or surgery [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . Hentschel and Sawaya emphasized the need for high quality imaging to detect recurring tumors, indicating that residual or satellite tumor cells have a potential of becoming even more aggressive and resistant to therapy, as compared to the original primary tumor [CITATION_9] .",
